To divide, multiply top and bottom by the conjugate of the denominator:

\[
\frac{1+6i}{6 - i}\;\times\;\frac{6+i}{6+i}
\;=\;\frac{(1+6i)(6+i)}{(6-i)(6+i)}
=\;\frac{6+ i +36i +6i^2}{36 - i^2}
=\;\frac{6+37i-6}{36+1}
=\;\frac{37i}{37}
=\;i.
\]

To write \(\frac{4}{1-4i}\) in standard form \(a+bi\), multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator:

\[
\frac{4}{1-4i}\;\times\;\frac{1+4i}{1+4i}
\;=\;\frac{4(1+4i)}{(1-4i)(1+4i)}
\;=\;\frac{4+16i}{1 - (4i)^2}
\;=\;\frac{4+16i}{1 - (-16)}
\;=\;\frac{4+16i}{17}
\;=\;\frac{4}{17} \;+\;\frac{16}{17}\,i.
\]

To divide \(-2\) by \(-1+2i\) and put the result in \(a+bi\) form, multiply top and bottom by the conjugate of the denominator:

\[
\frac{-2}{-1+2i}
=\frac{-2}{-1+2i}\cdot\frac{-1-2i}{-1-2i}
=\frac{(-2)(-1-2i)}{(-1)^2-(2i)^2}
=\frac{2+4i}{1-(-4)}
=\frac{2+4i}{5}
=\frac{2}{5}+\frac{4}{5}\,i.
\]

To simplify \((3+3i)/(2i)\), multiply top and bottom by \(-i\) (so the denominator becomes real):

\[
\frac{3+3i}{2i}\;\times\;\frac{-i}{-i}
\;=\;\frac{(3+3i)(-i)}{2i(-i)}
\;=\;\frac{-3i-3i^2}{-2i^2}
\;=\;\frac{-3i-3(-1)}{-2(-1)}
\;=\;\frac{-3i+3}{2}
\;=\;\frac{3}{2}-\frac{3}{2}i.
\]

Answer: \(\displaystyle \frac{3}{2}-\frac{3}{2}i\).

To divide by 5i, multiply top and bottom by –i:

\[
\frac{2+4i}{5i}\;=\;\frac{(2+4i)(-i)}{5i(-i)}
=\frac{4-2i}{5}
= \frac{4}{5}-\frac{2}{5}i.
\]
